## **üöÄ What Is Dependency Injection?**

**Dependency Injection** is a design pattern where an object receives its dependencies from an external source rather than creating them itself. In Spring Boot, this means the framework manages object creation and wiring, promoting loose coupling and easier testing.

---

## **üåü Why Is Dependency Injection Important?**

### **1\. Loose Coupling**

By injecting dependencies, classes are not tightly bound to specific implementations. This makes it easier to modify or replace components without affecting others. ## **üß† What is Dependency Injection?**

**Dependency Injection (DI)** is a design pattern that allows a class to receive its dependencies from external sources rather than creating them itself. In simpler terms, instead of a class creating its own objects, it gets them from an external source, promoting loose coupling and easier testing.

---

## **üß∞ How Does Spring Boot Handle DI with XML?**

In Spring Boot, you can define beans (objects) and their dependencies in an XML file. Here's how it works:

1. **Define Beans in XML**: You specify your beans and their dependencies in an XML file, typically named `applicationContext.xml`.

2. **Load XML Configuration**: Use the `@ImportResource` annotation in your main application class to load the XML configuration.

3. **Retrieve Beans**: Access the configured beans using the application context.

---

## **üìÑ Example: Coder and Computer Classes**

Let's consider two classes:

* `Computer`: Represents a computer with a brand.

* `Coder`: Represents a coder who uses a computer.

**Computer.java**

public class Computer {  
    private String brand;

    public Computer() {  
        System.out.println("Computer: no-arg constructor called");  
    }

    public void setBrand(String brand) {  
        this.brand \= brand;  
    }

    public String getBrand() {  
        return brand;  
    }  
}

**Coder.java**

public class Coder {  
    private int id;  
    private String name;  
    private String language;  
    private Computer computer;

    public Coder() {  
        System.out.println("Coder: no-arg constructor called");  
    }

    public void setId(int id) {  
        this.id \= id;  
    }

    public void setName(String name) {  
        this.name \= name;  
    }

    public void setLanguage(String language) {  
        this.language \= language;  
    }

    public void setComputer(Computer computer) {  
        this.computer \= computer;  
    }

    public void display() {  
        System.out.println("Coder ID: " \+ id);  
        System.out.println("Name: " \+ name);  
        System.out.println("Language: " \+ language);  
        System.out.println("Computer Brand: " \+ computer.getBrand());  
    }  
}

**applicationContext.xml**

\<beans xmlns="http://www.springframework.org/schema/beans"  
       xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"  
       xsi:schemaLocation="  
           http://www.springframework.org/schema/beans  
           http://www.springframework.org/schema/beans/spring-beans.xsd"\>

    \<bean id="computer" class="com.example.Computer"\>  
        \<property name="brand" value="Dell"/\>  
    \</bean\>

    \<bean id="coder" class="com.example.Coder"\>  
        \<property name="id" value="101"/\>  
        \<property name="name" value="Alice"/\>  
        \<property name="language" value="Java"/\>  
        \<property name="computer" ref="computer"/\>  
    \</bean\>

\</beans\>

**Main Application Class**

@SpringBootApplication  
@ImportResource("classpath:applicationContext.xml")  
public class SpringBootXmlApp {  
    public static void main(String\[\] args) {  
        ApplicationContext context \= SpringApplication.run(SpringBootXmlApp.class, args);  
        Coder coder \= context.getBean("coder", Coder.class);  
        coder.display();  
    }  
}

## **‚úÖ Benefits of Using XML Configuration**

* **Separation of Concerns**: Keeps configuration separate from code.

* **Flexibility**: Easily switch implementations by changing XML.

* **Legacy Support**: Useful when integrating with older Spring applications.

---

## **üìå Conclusion**

Using XML for dependency injection in Spring Boot allows you to manage object creation and wiring externally, promoting cleaner code and easier maintenance. While annotation-based configurations are more common in modern applications, understanding XML configuration is valuable, especially when working with legacy systems.
